    "text": "Primary adenoid cystic carcinoma of the thyroid gland : a case report and literature review.. Primary thyroid adenoid cystic carcinoma ( PT - ACC ) is an extremely rare malignant tumor, accounting for a negligible proportion of thyroid malignancies. It predominantly affects men and lacks unified clinical diagnostic criteria, resulting in a high rate of misdiagnosis. Owing to the scarcity of reported cases in female patients, we present this case with detailed ultrasonographic findings, pathological features, and 18 - month follow - up data to supplement clinical evidence in this underrepresented population and to aid differential diagnosis and treatment strategies. A 39 - year - old woman with a 2 - year history of hypertension, well controlled with oral medication, was found to have a thyroid nodule [ Thyroid Imaging Reporting and Data System ( TI - RADS ) category 4B ] during a routine physical examination in May 2021. Ultrasonography revealed a hypoechoic nodule measuring 20 mm × 16 mm × 24 mm located in the right thyroid lobe and isthmus, with an irregular shape",
